<AbstractNarration>Theoretical research will be carried out on the properties&lt;br/&gt;of objects with strong gravitational fields, such as neutron&lt;br/&gt;stars, black holes, and the Universe as a whole, with a particular&lt;br/&gt;focus on understanding the gravitational waves that such objects&lt;br/&gt;produce, and on developing and extending analytic approximation methods&lt;br/&gt;in general relativity to study these objects.  The particular&lt;br/&gt;objects to be studied include (i) newly born neutron stars in&lt;br/&gt;supernovae explosions, (ii) neutron stars and/or black holes&lt;br/&gt;spiralling into supermassive black holes in distant galaxies, and&lt;br/&gt;(iii) the dynamics of the very early Universe in models motivated by&lt;br/&gt;string theory with extra spatial dimensions and membranes.&lt;br/&gt;These studies will be useful in teaching us about the physics of&lt;br/&gt;relativistic gravitational fields, particularly when combined with&lt;br/&gt;future observational data from gravitational wave detectors and other&lt;br/&gt;sources.  &lt;br/&gt;</AbstractNarration>
